If $$z_1,...,z_n \in \mathbb{C}$$ are such that $$| z_i| \geq 1$$, how many of the $$2^n$$ sums $$\sum\limits_{i \in I} z_i$$, where $$I \subseteq [n]$$, can equal $$0$$? This question was raised in 1938, by Littlewood and Offord. A few years later, ErdÀùos found a neat solution in the real case.

See [[here|https://courses.maths.ox.ac.uk/node/view_material/33445]]

Theorem (Erdos). Suppose that $$x_1,...,x_n \in \mathbb{R}$$ satisfy $$|x_i| \geq 1$$ for all $$i$$. For every $$\alpha \in \mathbb{R}$$, there at most $$\binom{n}{\lfloor n/2 \rfloor}$$ subsets $$I \subseteq [n]$$ such that $$\sum_{i\in I} x_i \in [\alpha,\alpha+1)$$. Proof uses [[Sperner's lemma]]

